featured_reviews.review_id: Qadam-e-Rasul (Arabic: qdm lrswl) (English: Footprint of the Messenger) is a type of veneration of Muhammad. It comes from the belief started early in Islam that when Muhammad stepped on a rock his footprint left an imprint. This belief was never accepted by orthodox brands of Islam[citation needed]; however, the idea was disseminated widely and led to the creation of many shrines around such imprints.[1] Some examples are the Shrine of the Holy Footprint in Delhi and in Cuttack in India and the displays in the Topkapi Palace and the Eyup Sultan Mosque  at Istanbul.
